r, they believe, turns out to be less a matter of local traditions than of the ways that people perceive the patterns of their lives as being vulnerable to external forces of change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aLaw and anthropology. 0aLawxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSociological jurisprudence. 4aAnthropology. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History.1 aEngel, David M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aYngvesson, Barbara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172501240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501725012423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501725012/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_PPALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles